.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":31,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":62,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Malmains was born about 1228, in England, his father, Nicholas Malmains, was 26 and his mother, Beatrice Andeville, was 31. He had at least 2 sons with Agnes. He died about 1291, in Ockley, Surrey, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"about 1228–about 1291":"umbes 1228–umbes 1291","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1228–1291":"1228–1291","1228–1297":"1228–1297","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1204–1240":"1204–1240","1199–1240":"1199–1240","about 1291":"umbes 1291","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1259":"125